ch’, from Middle English <i>wak</i>, <i>wake</i> ‘wake, vigil, watch, period of guard duty’ (Old English <i>wacu</i>, Old Norse <i>vaka</i>). It alternates with the synonymous Middle English <i>wache</i> (Old English <i>wacce</i>), hence the variant <b>Watch</b>. The surname was also interchangeable with   Waite   (the equivalent Old French term) which, like <i>Wake</i>, was sometimes translated as Latin <i>vigil</i> ‘(one who is) watchful, alert’. Compare the synonymous   Vail  . When the bearers had high social status, the surname probably denoted an officer with responsibility for the security of a castle, town, or royal person. Compare   Wakeman  .","variant of   Wack  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vail","meanings":["English: occupational name from Old French <i>de la veille</i> ‘of the watch, watchman’, with loss of <i>de</i>; compare   Wake  . There has been some confusion with the topographic name   Vale   and the nickname   Veal  .","Scottish: shortened and altered form of   McPhail  , Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Phàil</b> ‘son of Paul’.","Irish: variant of   Veale  ."]},{"name":"Waite","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): occupational name for a watchman, either in a town or castle, from Anglo-Norman French <i>waite</i> ‘watchman, member of the watch’ (of ancient Germanic origin; compare   Wachter  ). In the Middle Ages the town waits typically combined the functions of watchmen and musicians through being trumpeters or pipers. There may also have been some late confusion with   White   or   Wheat  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Lewis   or respelling of   Lou  , as borne by the impresario  Lew Grade  (  1906–98 , originally  Louis Winogradsky )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret le Wake was born about 1156, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Reiner Waterton."},"et":{"about 1156–":"umbes 1156–Surnud","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","1178–1225":"1178–1225","1156–Female":"1156–Surnud","1225":"1225","1156":"1156","1178":"1178","about 1156":"umbes 1156","about 1178":"umbes 1178","1150":"1150",",Lincolnshire,England.":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1156–":"noin 1156–Kuollut","1150–Male":"1150–Kuollut","1178–1225":"1178–1225","1156–Female":"1156–Kuollut","1225":"1225","1156":"1156","1178":"1178","about 1156":"noin 1156","about 1178":"noin 1178","1150":"1150",",Lincolnshire,England.":"Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Of England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1156–":"environ 1156–Décédée","1150–Male":"1150–Décédé","1178–1225":"1178–1225","1156–Female":"1156–Décédée","1225":"1225","1156":"1156","1178":"1178","about 1156":"environ 1156","about 1178":"environ 1178","1150":"1150",",Lincolnshire,England.":"Lincolnshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Of England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Margaret le Wake est née environ 1156, à Lincolnshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Reiner Waterton."},"de":{"about 1156–":"um 1156–Verstorben","1150–Male":"1150–Verstorben","1178–1225":"1178–1225","1156–Female":"1156–Verstorben","1225":"1225","1156":"1156","1178":"1178","about 1156":"um 1156","about 1178":"um 1178","1150":"1150",",Lincolnshire,England.":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Of England":"England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Margaret le Wake wurde um 1156 in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom geboren. Sie hatte mit Reiner Waterton mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"about 1156–":"about 1156–Desede","1150–Male":"1150–D